<subSubSection id="A61AACBCF7A0F98BFC0689B841068AEC" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A680794DE7F93E533AACE24F1997219C" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="833BA99C24DFDB55DC09CB8E74143F5B" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
Scape with outer face yellow but with black strip along dorsal margin; scape 4.0
<normalizedToken id="792A9407D4524F87B857DB590CDD9C15" originalValue="–4.8×">-4.8x</normalizedToken>
as long as broad; funicle with F1 smallest, F2-F6 becoming larger towards apex, F2-F6 with linear sensilla (Fig. 22); fore wing hyaline, with linea calva uninterrupted (Fig. 24); ovipositor strongly exserted, and about 2
<normalizedToken id="7C9FA0929167A08233609E00430EC93B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as mid tibia (Fig. 28). 
<taxonomicName id="E2669A16831FEB25F16270D934C736B4" class="Insecta" family="Encyrtidae" genus="Metaphycus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metaphycus gerardi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gerardi">Metaphycus gerardi</taxonomicName>
is very close to 
<taxonomicName id="C097C1E17BE0AC64034356C408F3870E" class="Insecta" family="Encyrtidae" genus="Metaphycus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metaphycus eruptor" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eruptor">Metaphycus eruptor</taxonomicName>
(Howard, 1881) in appearance. They share similar antennal structure, fore wing shape and ovipositor dimensions. Further studies may show they are synonyms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
